Main US - Univariate analysis

Fabio Torreggiani

Created: 30th November 2023; Updated:

Purpose: Running descriptive analysis on all the measured variables, divided by mechanism and, when needed, compared with either the reference population.

Summary

  • Twitter. Half of the sample has it and uses it regularly, especially for lurking (74% at least once a week; 60% for active use).

  • Cognitive effort. Tasks where quite difficult: 73% of sample got 0 correct, another 15% got just one correct and only around 5% got all correct.

  • Politics. If we look at party affiliation Democrats are over-represented. If we look at political orientation, Left-Right orientation present a quasi-normal distribution, with anchoring on the extremes and at the center, with a lot of people in the center of the scale, but more people on the right than on the left.

  • Institutions. Problematic percentage of I prefer not to answer on trust in Parliament (11%). Relatively low trust, but higher than in italian case. All institutions with mean below middle point of the scale, except for Universities. Social media have the lowest trust (mean 0.41/1). Social media the one with highest SD, but not radically different from others. In general, Press, Parliament and Government have the more similar distributions. Trust in science is pretty high according to both measures. Other considerations in PCA report.

  • Anti-elitism. Distributions are very different to the Italian case. Similarly to Italy, the distribution of the first item (politicians talk too much), is squeezed to the top of the scale. However, the second item (differences between people and the elite) have high frequencies from the middle to the top of the scale. Surprisingly, the third item (politicians think about the people) is almost a flat distribution. Similarly to the Italian case, the third item is the most (negatively) correlated with trust in institutions. This was partially the case also for the first item, which here is not correlated at all with institutions. Interestingly, the second item is here positively (slightly) correlated with trust in institutions.

  • Social Norms - Beliefs. Clear and strong preference for accuracy. This is especially true for personal normative beliefs, where 60% put accuracy as their first priority. This is an indication that participants understood the questions and that there is a fraction of people recognizing that they value interest when they should value accuracy.

  • Social Norms - Expectations. People are quite good at guessing the unclear/mixed situation regarding the norm. The mode answer is more or less half of the sample, followed by around three quarter. This result is true for both empirical and normative expectations and it is the same as in the Italian convenience sample. Also, there is a link between beliefs and expectations, but not a very strong one: the incidence of people choosing accuracy is higher in those who put almost everyone and three quarters, especially for the normative expectations.

  • Media Consumption. The most consumed media are internet, phones and tv news, which are consumed more ore less by everyone and on a very frequent base. Other media are more niche, in the sense that they have both people using them a lot and others using them never or very rarely: social media and emails. Friends are consumed by more or less everyone, but with varying frequency. Traditional media, like newspapers and radionews appears to be much less used than in the Italian sample, although they still have around 40% of the sample using them at least once a week. Differently from the Italian sample, in all media there is around 20% of the sample who never uses it. This highlights a more fragmented media world with some people completely avoding certain media.

  • Perceived Accuracy. Sort of bi-modal, but not coinciding with the two extremes: extremely accurate is the least chosen category. In general, people were both skeptical (generally low scores, even for reliable news), and good at discerning news (still, there is a gap between fake and reliable news). Interestingly, the most chosen category is I dont know, highlighting a more cautious approach to news evaluation.

  • Perceived Accuracy - Events. Differently to what noted in other studies (preparatory studies and the convenience sample), people were good at discerning news, independently of the event analysed. For 15 out of 20 events the reliable news is significantly perceived as more accurate than the fake news. Then, there are five events for which the scores are not statistically distinguishable between the true and fake news. This result could also be simply due to the higher numerosity of the sample.

  • Perceived Accuracy - Round and Treatment. No effect of round: people are not better (nor worse) as the survey proceed. No effect of treatment: truth discernment is not better or worse after the treatment, in none of the groups.

  • Robustness Checks - Individual Perceived Accuracy. In general, the distribution is very close to a normal one. Divided by veracity, the curve for fake news is squeezed toward the bottom of the scale and seems cut: a lot of people choose the bottom of the scale for fake news. Individual truth discernment present a normal distribution with and a relatively strong right skewness: there are a lot of people with positive truth discernment and there are some with perfect or almost perfect scores.

  • Robustness Checks - Balance of news. The balance of news (% of fake news over the ten items) is a normal distribution (randomization worked correctly). There is no effect of balance on truth discernment: people judged items one by one, without inferring the balance of true vs fake news and trying to guess the accuracy based on that.

  • Sharing behavior. As expected, it is a very rare behaviour and linked with perceived accuracy (correlation of 0.5), although weakly so and much weakly if compared to the italian sample.

myBarPlot <- function(var_n){
  ggplot(aes(x = .data[[var_n]]), data = part_df) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = (..count..)/sum(..count..))) +
  guides(x = guide_axis(n.dodge = 2)) +
  labs(x = var_n, y = "frequency") +
  scale_x_discrete(label = function(x) stringr::str_trunc(x, 30)) +
  coord_flip()
}

mySummary <- function(var_n){
  a <- sprintf("Summary of: %s", var_n)
  b <- part_df[[paste0(var_n, "Num")]] %>% summary()
  c <- sprintf("Mean: %.3f", mean(part_df[[paste0(var_n, "Num")]], na.rm = T))
  d <- sprintf("Sd: %.3f", sd(part_df[[paste0(var_n, "Num")]], na.rm = T))
  cat(a, "\n")
  print(b)
  cat(c, d)
}

Trust in institutions

my_plot <- function(data, x){
  p <- ggplot(data,
         aes(x = .data[[x]])) +
    geom_bar() +
    theme(legend.position = "none") +
    ylim(0,300)
  #return(p)
}

my_plot <- function(data, x){
  p <- ggplot(data,
         aes(x = .data[[x]])) +
    geom_bar(aes(y = after_stat(count/sum(count)))) +
    theme(legend.position = "none") +
    ylim(0,0.25) +
    labs(y = "Frequency")
  #return(p)
}

var_n = "IT_Press"
var_i = match(var_n, names(part_df))

inst <- names(part_df)[var_i:(var_i + 4)]

l <- lapply(inst, my_plot, data = part_df)
ggpubr::ggarrange(l[[1]], l[[2]], l[[3]], l[[4]],
                  l[[5]],
                  ncol=3, nrow=2, common.legend = TRUE, legend="bottom") %>% print()

my_plot <- function(data, x){
  p <- ggplot(data,
         aes(x = .data[[x]])) +
    geom_histogram(aes(y = after_stat(count/sum(count)))) +
    theme(legend.position = "none") +
    ylim(0,0.5) +
    #xlim(0,1.2) +
    labs(x = lbls[[x]],
         y = "Frequency")
  #return(p)
}

Avg. Perc. per Event

sum_event <- answ_df %>% group_by(event) %>%
  summarise(
    n = n(),
    avg_Fake = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"])$estimate,
    lci_Fake = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"])$conf.int[1],
    uci_Fake = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"])$conf.int[2],
    avg_Rel = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$estimate,
    lci_Rel = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$conf.int[1],
    uci_Rel = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$conf.int[2],
    avg_Diff = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"],
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$estimate[1] -
      t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"],
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$estimate[2],
    lci_Diff = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"],
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$conf.int[1],
    uci_Diff = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"],
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$conf.int[2],
    p_val = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"],
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$p.value,
    sign_Diff = ifelse(p_val < 0.05, 1, 0),
    highest = max(avg_Fake, avg_Rel)
  )
sum_event %>% pivot_longer(cols = -c(event, n, avg_Diff, lci_Diff, uci_Diff, p_val, sign_Diff, highest),
               names_to = c(".value", "veracity"),
               names_sep = "_",
               values_drop_na = T) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(event, avg_Diff), y = avg, fill = veracity)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position = position_dodge()) +
  labs(x = "Events",
       y = "Perceived accuracy",
       caption = paste0("Stars indicate that, for a specific event,
       \nthe avg. perc. acc. is significanlty different between the fake and rel. post.
                        \n\nEvents for which diff. is not sign. at 95% level: ",
                         paste(as.character(sum_event$event[sum_event$sign_Diff == 0]), collapse = " "))) +
  geom_text(aes(label = ifelse(sign_Diff, "*", ""), y = highest, group = event),
            vjust = -.1, hjust = .5, size = 20 / .pt) +
  ylim(0,4) +
  theme(plot.caption = element_text(lineheight = .5))

  geom_histogram(aes(y = after_stat(count/sum(count))), bins = 18) +
  labs(x = "Average score per participant", y = "Frequency",
       caption = "Each bar represent how many part. gave that specific avg. score to all the (either fake oe reliable) items he or she saw") +
  facet_grid(cols = vars(veracity))

Truth discern. per Id

answ_df %>% filter(!is.na(ACCNum)) %>% group_by(id, veracity) %>%
  summarise(avg = mean(ACCNum)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = "veracity", values_from =  "avg") %>%
  mutate(avg_Diff = Reliable - Fake) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = avg_Diff)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  labs(x = "\nAverage diff. of perc. acc. of rel. news minus that of fake news,
       calculated on individual basis")
